description._value: High Intensity Exercise (HIE) stimulates greater physiological remodeling when compared to workload matched low-moderate intensity exercise. This study utilized an untargeted metabolomics approach to examine the metabolic perturbations that occur following two workload matched supramaximal low volume HIE trials. In a randomized order, 7 untrained males completed two exercise protocols separated by one week; 1) HIE150%: 30 x 20s cycling at 150% VO2peak, 40s passive rest; 2) HIE300%: 30 x 10s cycling at 300% VO2peak, 50 s passive rest. Total exercise duration was 30 minutes for both trials. Blood samples were taken at rest, during and immediately following exercise and at 60 minutes post exercise. Gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS) analysis of plasma identified 55 metabolites of which 8 demonstrated significant fold changes (HIE300% compared to the HIE150% value) during exercise, 22 post exercise and 32 at the end of the recovery period. Significant changes in plasma metabolites relating to lipid metabolism [fatty acids: dodecanoate (p=0.042), hexadecanoate (p=0.001), octadecanoate (p=0.001)], total cholesterol (p=0.001), and glycolysis [lactate (p=0.018)] were observed following exercise and during the recovery period. The HIE300% protocol elicited greater metabolic changes relating to lipid metabolism and glycolysis when compared to HIE150% protocol. These changes were more pronounced throughout the recovery period rather than during the exercise bout itself. Data from the current study demonstrates the use of metabolomics to monitor intensity-dependent changes in multiple metabolic pathways following exercise.

50 µL of each lithium heparin treated plasma sample was diluted with 150 µL of MeOH [spiked with 4% 13C6-Sorbitol as an extraction internal standard (ISTD)]. The samples were briefly vortexed and placed on ice for 10 mins prior to being centrifuged at 13,200 rpm for 5 mins at 4 °C to precipitate any protein present. 100 µL supernatant was separated and transferred into 6 mm diameter conical bottom glass vial inserts that had been placed inside eppendorf vials. An additional 10 µL supernatant from each extracted sample was combined into a separate eppendorf vial, which was vortexed and used to create 5 x 100 µL pooled biological quality control (PBQC) glass vial inserts. Eppendorf vials containing inserts were then dried in vacuo at a temperature of -55 °C and pressure of 3 mbar for 2 hrs. Glass vial inserts were then placed into 2 ml wide top glass vials and covered with metallic crimp caps (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, USA). Additional glass vials containing MeOX (methyloxime) (10 µL per sample) and TMS (trimethysilyl) (20 µL per sample) were prepared for derivatisation.

The GC-MS system used comprised of a 7890A Agilent gas chromatograph triple-quadrupole and a 5975C Agilent triple-axis mass selective detector (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, USA). A Gerstal Technologies MPS2XL GC-MS autosampler was set to select samples for analysis in a randomized order. MeOX and TMS derivatized samples were injected onto the GC column using a hot needle technique. The injection was operated in both a splitless (1 ųl sample) and split (0.20 ųl sample) modes to avoid overloaded chromatogram peaks. An inlet temperature of 230°C and helium was used as the carrier gas with a flow rate of 1 ml per min along a 30 m VF-5MS column with 0.25 µm film thickness, and a 10 m Integra guard column, for chromatographic separation.

The GC-MS system used comprised of a 7890A Agilent gas chromatograph triple-quadrupole and a 5975C Agilent triple-axis mass selective detector (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, USA). 
The MS transfer line to the quadrupole was fixed at 280°C, the EI ion source fixed at 250 °C, and the MS quadrupole fixed at 150 °C. The oven set up for sample analysis was: injection temperature of 70 °C for a 1 minute hold, followed by 1 °C per min  increase to 76 °C (with no hold), and a 7 °C per min  increase to a final temperature of 325 °C for a 5 min hold. The GC-MS system was equilibrated for 1 min at 70 °C prior to the injection of the next sample. Ions were generated by a 70 eV electron beam at an ionization current of 2.0 mA and spectra were recorded at 2.91 scans per second with a mass-to-charge ratio of 50 to 550 atomic mass units (amu) scanning range.

An Automated Mass Spectral Deconvolution and Identification System (AMDIS) was used to analyze the chromatogram. A random PBQC was used for data filtering (to remove background noise), deconvolution (to align peaks and correct for retention time drifts between runs) and peak detection (via characteristics of each ion including m/z ratio, retention time and ion intensity). Using the in house Metabolomics Australia (University of Melbourne, Australia) mass spectra library the mass spectra was then additionally verified by analysis of reference standard compounds.  MassHunter was then used to analyze the relative response ratio for each detected peak (the area of each unique ion) from a randomly selected PBQC, prior to being applied to the remainder of the batch. Overloaded peaks (lactate, glucose, mannose, sucrose, fructose, urea and cholesterol) were analyzed separately from the split mode. Relative response ratio data for each compound detected in each sample was normalized to the ISTD (13C6-Sorbitol). MetaboAnalyst 2.0 was used to generate multivariate analysis pattern analysis models. PCA analysis was performed using the prcomp function. Additional normalization via a generalized log transformation was applied to the data matrix used in order to improve symmetry prior to PC generation. Seven healthy recreationally active males were asked to complete two supramaximal low volume HIE protocols in a randomized order and separated by at least one week: 1) HIE150%: 30 x 20 s cycling at 150% VO2peak, 40 s passive rest (348 ± 27 W); 2) HIE300%: 30 x 10 s cycling at 300% VO2peak, 50 s passive rest (697 ± 54 W). Exercise trials were 30 mins in duration and workload matched by manipulating exercise intensity and the duration of cycling and rest intervals. HIE was preceded by a rest period and followed by 60 min passive recovery in a supine position. Blood was sampled at rest, 10 mins into exercise (EX10), immediately after exercise (EX30) and at the end of the 60 min recovery period (RC60). Samples were immediately placed into lithium heparin tubes and centrifuged at 12,000 rpm for 2 mins. Plasma was decanted and stored at -80 °C for later GCMS analysis.

title._value: The use of metabolomics to monitor simultaneous changes in metabolic variables following supramaximal low volume high intensity exercise
